	<section id="full-intro">
		<div class="container">
			<div class="row">
			  <div class="col-sm-12">
				  <h2>23 DESTINATIONS LAST PLACES WEST AFRICA</h2>
					<h3>Western Sahara</h3>
				  <p><strong>What does it offer?</strong><br>
Western Sahara is currently part of  the Kingdom of Morocco. Until 1975 it was a Spanish colony and still older  people speak Spanish. The combination of local Saharan culture and Spanish  colonial heritage gives this destination a unique flavor.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Colonial Spanish cities with  rationalist architecture of the 1950s-1960s.<br>
                      -Virgin beaches with monk seal  populations<br>
                      -Nomadic Saharawi Culture</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Western Sahara:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      For many European nationalities a  tourist visa is not necessary. Other nationalities, consult.</p>
                    <p><strong>Mandatory vaccines in Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      There are no mandatory vaccines.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      The Western Sahara is safe in  general but it is a peculiar territory since there is a strong pro-independence  social movement and there have been armed activity in areas of the interior of  the territory between the Polisario (armed independence group) and the  Government of Rabat. To visit the coastal area you do not have to obtain a travel  permit. For the interior it is necessary to have a travel permit that Last  Places West Africa helps to manage. It is important to find out about the  potentially mined areas on the border with Algeria and Morocco.<br>
  <strong>Money in Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      The Moroccan Dirham is used and can  easily be exchanged for Euros.<br>
  <strong>Time in Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging camera / mobile batteries in  Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 220 V Plugs: Type C  Frequency: 50 Hz<br>
                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.<br>
  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
  <strong>Best time to travel to Western Sahara - Climate of  Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips throughout the year, but between November and January the heat is not so  strong. <br>
  <strong>Eating in Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      The traditional drink is the green  tea of ​​China, flavored with mint leaves, as happens in other regions of North  Africa.<br>
                      If you do not have prejudices at  lunchtime, you can try the milk of fresh camel or curd, known as  &quot;zrigh&quot;. Taste the dishes of lamb or camel meat, presented in a  unique container, in which everyone can serve with the right hand (the left is  reserved for intimate hygiene).<br>
                      As for the garnish, you'll find  couscous, rice, sorghum or millet. On the coast you can savor grilled fish and  lobsters. Tea and dates are part of every good meal worthy of its name.</p>
                    <p><strong>Photography in Western Sahara</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings, or political  demonstrations.</p>
                    <p><strong>Mauritania</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>What does Mauritania offer?</strong><br>
                      Mauritania is a desert country with  a lot of personality. It has cultural links with Western Sahara and with Mali.  The great attraction is its people, who still dress in a traditional way in its  majority, the interior desert and the historic cities. In a few days the  traveler can enjoy a very peculiar country, authentic, and with touches of  controlled adventure.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      - Historic cities of Ouadane,  Chingetti, Tichitt, and Oualata<br>
                      -Parque Nacional de  Banc d'Arguin<br>
                      - Tagant rock paintings<br>
                      - N'Madi nomadic tribes<br>
                      -Adrar Valley with oases and dune  areas</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Mauritania:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Mauritania</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Mauritania.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Mauritania</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended prophylaxis  against malaria but in the desert there is little mosquito.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Mauritania</strong><br>
                      The country is quite safe in  general but the authorities ask for caution on the border with Mali (Oualata  zone) due to the insecurity of Mali and isolated cases of banditry.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Mauritania</strong><br>
                      The official currency of Mauritania  is the Ouguiya. You can get change in the banks of the big cities. Some hotels,  as well as Mauritanians that you will find on the street (especially in the  capital) can offer you a currency exchange.<br>
                      In Mauritania the places that allow  paying by credit card are counted, so money must be carried in cash.</p>
                    <p><strong>Time in Mauritania</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1.</p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging cameras / mobiles in  Mauritania</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 220 V Plugs: Type C  Frequency: 50 Hz<br>
                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Mauritania - Climate of  Mauritania</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips throughout the year.<br>
                      That said, from November to March  are the most pleasant months to go to the desert, although nights can be cold.<br>
                      From June to August the rifi (warm  winds) cause temperatures to exceed 45 ° C, and from July to September there is  a brief rainy season in Nouakchott, the capital of Mauritania, can cause  flooding after the downpours.</p>
                    <p><strong>Eating in Mauritania</strong><br>
                      In Mauritania, the national drink  is Chinese green tea, flavored with mint leaves, as in other regions of North  Africa. If the case arises, take the opportunity to attend, under a tent, the  ritual of the three teas, which starts with the bitterest until the softest.<br>
                      If you do not have prejudices at  lunchtime, you can try the milk of fresh camel or curd, known as  &quot;zrigh&quot;. Taste the dishes of lamb or camel meat, presented in a  unique container, in which everyone can serve with the right hand (the left is  reserved for intimate hygiene).<br>
                      As for the garnish, you'll find  couscous, rice, sorghum or millet. In the capital Nouakchott, you can savor  grilled fish and lobsters. Tea and dates are part of every good meal worthy of  its name.</p>
                    <p><strong>Photography in Mauritania</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or police  controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission to  take pictures of people or their houses.<br>
  <strong>Books about Mauritania</strong></p>
                    <p><strong><em>Last Tribes of Mauritania, Mali, Burkina Faso, and  Niger</em></strong> By Last Places</p>
                    <p><strong>Senegal</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>What does Senegal offer?</strong><br>
                      Senegal is often seen as the  gateway to 'authentic' Black Africa away from the themed world of safaris. For  Last Places West Africa, Senegal is a country that has its surprises despite  the mass tourism of some parts of the country (coast of Saly, Bassari Hills...).  The north of Senegal is very interesting, with few tourists, nomadic tribes  that still tattoo their lips, and the sinuous Senegal River, crossed by old  stone and adobe forts of the French colonial era. A good trip through Senegal  should end in Saint Louis, an architectural gem that stands stopped in time.<br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Calmly walk the streets of Saint  Louis in North Senegal.<br>
                      -Explore the Ferlo Desert, between  Touba and the Senegal River.<br>
                      -Know the Fula nomads. Fula women  continue tattooing their lips with a kind of blue ink.<br>
                      -Visit Dakar and its museums. Take  the ferry to Goree Island (touristy but cute).<br>
                      -Visit Touba on a Friday, see the  Muslim prayer in front of the largest mosque in Africa. A visual spectacle</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Senegal:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Senegal</strong><br>
                      No tourist visa is necessary for most  European nationalities. </p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccines in Senegal</strong><br>
                      None. Recommended prophylaxis  against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Senegal</strong><br>
                      Senegal is one of the safest  countries in West Africa. That said, it is advisable to take precautions in  large cities such as Dakar or San Luis and avoid driving at night (through the  crossing of cattle).</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Senegal</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the CFA  Franc, common currency in several countries (former French colonies) of West  and Central Africa. You can exchange Euros for the local currency at airports,  banks, or exchange houses. The Last Places West Africa guide can help you  exchange money. The places that allow paying by credit card are counted, so  money must be carried in cash.</p>
                    <p><strong>Schedule in Senegal</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1</p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging batteries cameras / mobiles  in Senegal</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 220 V Plugs: Type C  Frequency: 50 Hz<br>
                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.<br>
  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
  <strong>Best time to travel to Senegal - Climate of Senegal</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips to Senegal throughout the year. The dry season goes from the end of  October to June. During the rains (June-October) everything can be done, they  do not impede the trip except in some northern areas.</p>
                    <p><strong>Eating in Senegal</strong><br>
                      The national dish is  tiep-bou-diene, an appetizing stew of rice with vegetables and fish. Meats such  as ox, lamb and chicken are marinated with a peanut sauce that gives them a  unique flavor characteristic of the country. In the coastal areas of the  country you should try the fish and seafood; prawns, lobsters, sea oxen, and a  long list of fresh and tasty products caught early in the day. In the jungle  areas, game meat seems to be the most outstanding delicacy for the inhabitants  of the country.</p>
                    <p><strong>Photography in Senegal</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.</p>
                    <p><strong>Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Guinea Conakry offer?</strong><br>
                      Guinea Conakry, also known as  Guinea (French Guinea) is a pretty closed country, with very little tourism.  The country's authorities are focused on the mining industry, and tourism is  seen as something exotic and distant ... In Last Places West Africa we believe  in the potential of Guinea Conakry and we think is a country worth discovering,  at least once in a lifetime. In the Fouta Djalon Mountains the mythical Niger  River is born, but the area is especially interesting for being the cultural  and spiritual center of the great Fula nation (Fulani, Peul, Pulo, Woodabe,  Mbororo, Falata) that extends from Guinea to Sudan, through the arid African  Sahel. Culture, landscape, and vernacular architecture give a special flavor to  this destination. Alongside this mountainous region, there are several isolated  tribes each with their identity and ritual masks.<br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -The chaos of capital Conakry and  the Islands of Loos to disconnect from chaos.<br>
                      - Fouta Djalon Mountains, Fulani  villages, straw mosques, and adobe architecture.<br>
                      - Baga, Nimba, Banda masquerades on  the border of Ivory Coast and Liberia.<br>
                      - Basari and Koniagi initiation  rites of passage in the mountains near Senegal border.<br>
                      - Mount Nimba Nature Reserve.  Divided between Ivory Coast and Guinea Conakry, UNESCO World Heritage. It is rich  in wildlife with no less than 200 endemic species. It is ideal for trekking.<br>
                      -Ziama Forest: This virgin forest  is one of the last remaining forests in Guinea Conakry. It is a refuge for the Guinea  elephants and many unique plants and animal species.<br>
                      -Bridges: Located on the Oule  River, they are among the most interesting examples of indigenous engineering  in Guinea. The longest tracks between Koladou village and Kissidigou. Other  examples can be found in wooded areas, such as the village of Koya.<br>
                      -Faranah is known for its great  mosque and markets. It is also in a river (source of Niger), which flows from  Foroknia to Bamako. On the river bank there are many interesting settlements.<br>
                      -Le Voile de la Mariée Waterfall:  One of the most beautiful waterfalls in the country.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Guinea Conakry:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Guinea Conakry. Last Places West Africa helps manage it.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      Guinea Conakry is a safe country in  general. It has to be watched in the capital (petty theft) and not driving at  night as roads and tracks are generally in poor condition. Patience with police  and military controls. Country remove corrupt and with a few tourists, this  means that they stop with Westerners ask for some kind of 'gift'. The Guide of  Last Places West Africa is responsible for managing these situations.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the French  Guinean (GNF). ATMs are non-existent and credit cards have limited acceptance  throughout the country. You have to bring cash.</p>
                    <p><strong>Time in Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging camera / mobile batteries in  Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 220 V Plugs: Type C  Frequency: 50 Hz<br>
                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Guinea Conakry - Guinea Conakry  Weather</strong><br>
                      Guinea Conakry enjoys a tropical  climate, especially in the coastal region and inland areas. The climate is  pleasant throughout the year, with average temperatures of 29 ° C and average  minimum of 13 °. The rainy season usually lasts from April to November, and the  country receives an annual rainfall of up to 2,786 cm³. In the high region,  near the border with Mali, the temperatures are warmer, and the rainy season is  shorter. Because of all this, the best time to visit Guinea Conakry is between  November and December, just after the rainy season and before the beginning of  the Harmattan dust winds. The rainy season can make the secondary roads  impassable, although it is when the field is greener, the waterfalls more  spectacular and the temperatures more pleasant. Last Places West Africa  organizes trips throughout the year.</p>
                    <p><strong>Eating in Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      In addition to African dishes of  local cuisine, in large cities you will find international cuisine. A typical  dish consists of rice with meat or fish and accompanied with one of the four  main sauces. Pork is only served in areas where Islam is not practiced.  Throughout Guinea Conakry, there are decent restaurants not only in the capital  and Faranah and European and Lebanese food restaurants dot most of the cities.<br>
                      In the capital, Conakry, you will  find French, Asian and Middle Eastern cuisine. The restaurants are usually  close to the coast. An example is La Plage Rogbane (Taouyah, Conakry), which is  hidden in an alley near the beach, an ideal place to enjoy the sea; Belvedere  (Route de Donka Bellevue, Conakry) is also a place worth trying, known for its  sandwiches, pizzas and meats.<br>
  <strong>Photography in Guinea Conakry</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.</p>
                    <p><strong>Guinea-Bissau</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>What does Guinea Bissau offer?</strong><br>
                      Guinea Bissau also known as Portuguese  Guinea is an African jewel stopped in time. This, is a phenomenon very typical  of the Portuguese ex-colonies. After Independence in 1975, the economic system  imploded Implosion and the country has remained paralyzed since then ... The  decadent architecture, a primitive rural world and the wonderful Bijagos  islands with a unique culture in Africa based on a matriarchal system, make  Guinea Bissau a very attractive destination.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -The archipelago of the Bijagos Islands  consists of more than 18 small islands, some of which are inhabited, but rarely  visited by travelers. In some more remote islands, like Uno, you can still find  women from the Bijagos tribe wearing the traditional raffia skirt daily. The  Bijagos tribe is matriarchal and of Animistic religion. In some clans, corporal  scarification is still practiced.<br>
                      -Bissau: Travel through time around  the rustic but vibrant capital of Bissau. The city has a wide range of  attractions that date back to the Portuguese colonial. <br>
                      -Cacheu, a city located on the  banks of the Cacheu River, this port has a 16th century fortress.<br>
                      -Cantanhez Natural Park, is a  community-based conservation project established to protect the region's  wildlife such as the Guinean chimpanzee.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Guinea Bissau:</strong><br>
                      <strong>Tourist visa to travel to Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Guinea Bissau. It can be obtained at the Embassy of Guinea Bissau in  Lisbon, Portugal or upon arrival with a certified letter that Last Places West  Africa helps manage.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      Guinea Bissau has had episodes of  political and social instability since its independence from Portugal in 1975.  It is a very poor country with high rates of corruption. That means that the  traveler will be constantly exposed to blackmail by police and local  authorities. In rural areas and on the islands, the situation is much more  relaxed.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      The CFA Franc is the official  currency of Guinea Bissau. There are ATMs in the capital and other major cities  and traveler's checks are rarely accepted. Leave your credit cards at home, as  they are of very limited use in the capital and are completely useless outside  of Bissau.</p>
                    <p><strong>Schedule in Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging cameras / mobiles in Guinea  Bissau</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 220 V Plugs: Type C  Frequency: 50 Hz<br>
                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Guinea Bissau - Guinea Bissau  Weather</strong><br>
                      Guinea Bissau has a tropical  climate that experiences warm weather and humidity throughout the year, with  very little temperature fluctuations. The daily average is 26 °, higher during  the dry season (usually from December to April) before the rainy season. The  highest rains occur between June and October. During the dry season, the dusty  wind of the harmattan can be unpleasant for trips to the beach. The best time  to visit Guinea-Bissau is between November and February, when temperatures are  relatively cold and the ground is dry. The climate is perfect for jumping from  island to island in the Bijagos archipelago and visiting the natural parks. It  is best to avoid the potential monsoons of the rainy season, as it can make  travel difficult. Last Places West Africa organizes trips throughout the year.<br>
  <strong>Eating in Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      The restaurant offer in Guinea  Bissau is not as great as in other West African countries with more developed  tourist infrastructures. However, eating out (especially in the capital) can be  enjoyable. Hotels usually have their own restaurants in the house and you can  find many establishments near the center of the city.<br>
                      A typical dish from Guinea consists  of rice and fish, which are plentiful and relatively cheap throughout the  country. Dishes containing beef, chicken, pork and goat meat are also  available, often served with different types of sauces, peanuts, palm oil and  vegetables. Some Guineans also enjoy wild game meat. The street stalls sell  snacks, tortillas, boiled eggs, donuts and cakes.<br>
  <strong>Photography in Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.<br>
  <strong>Books about Guinea Bissau</strong><br>
  <strong><em>Last Tribes of Guinea Bissau, Sierra Leone, Liberia  and Ivory Coast.</em></strong> By Last Places</p>
                    <p><strong>Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Sierra Leone offer?</strong><br>
                      Sierra Leone surprises positively.  Small country without apparent attractiveness or nothing special with respect  to other West African countries ... Well, that is not the case. Sierra Leone is  a unique country that is worth discovering. On the one hand it displays a  unique history of returned slaves from different parts of the world. On the  second hand there are hundreds of female secret societies (Sande). Last but not  least Sierra Leone has some of Africa&rsquo;s best beaches. Sierra Leone has had a  difficult history, and being a diamond producer has not helped its stability  but the country is ideally sized to explore without rushing.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Rituals and dances with masks Poro  and Sande of the Mende and Tenme tribes<br>
                      -Freetown and its wonderful Creole  houses<br>
                      -The popular ferry that connects  the international airport with Freetown, there is no better way to start a  trip...<br>
                      - National Park of Tiwai Island<br>
                      -Giant masquerades giants of the Animist  tribe Limba (North)</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to Travel to Sierra Leone:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Sierra Leone. Last Places West Africa helps to manage the visa.</p>
                    <p><strong>Mandatory vaccines in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      Sierra Leone is a safe country in  general and the police do not overwhelm much in the controls (there are not  many either). Try not to travel at night by the state of roads and tracks.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      The currency of legal tender in  Sierra Leone is the Sierra Leonean Leone (&quot;Le&quot;, SLL). The use of  electronic cards is limited to international hotels in Freetown so it is  recommended to take cash and change it upon arrival.</p>
                    <p><strong>Schedule in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging batteries cameras / mobiles  in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      In Sierra Leone the common voltage  is 230 V. The frequency is 50 Hz. The plugs are of type D / G.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Sierra Leone - Sierra Leone  Weather</strong><br>
                      The best time is from November to  June (dry season). Dust and heat but possibility to reach all places without  problem and enjoy the beaches. Daytime socks of 32 ° C. From June to November  we have the rainy season: spectacular storms and rainfall of up to 3200 mm.  Last Places West Africa organizes trips throughout the year.</p>
                    <p><strong>Eating in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      The cuisine of Sierra Leone is very  tasty and varied, the result of the different cultures that have passed there,  which makes it very international.<br>
                      Among the most common ingredients  of homemade recipes, we should mention rice, peanuts, corn, yams, cassava, fish  and a great variety of seafood, given its proximity to the sea, especially  lobsters and Atlantic prawns.</p>
                    <p>About rice, it can be said that it  is the fundamental product in the diet of this country, with which the most  typical dishes are prepared. It is usually mixed with a sauce of okra or okra,  a plant that grows wild and has a taste similar to that of eggplant and that  through the slaves that came to America, it is consumed almost all Latin  America and in the Caribbean islands especially, where it is part of their most  typical dishes such as &quot;Calalu&quot;. In the streets it is very common to  find food stalls that offer a wide variety of products, such as roasted peanuts  and corn, veal sticks, fried plantains, potatoes with fish sauce, etc.<br>
                      <strong>Photography in Sierra Leone</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or police  controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission to  take pictures of people or their houses.<br>
  <strong>Books about Sierra Leone</strong><br>
  <strong><em>Last Tribes of Guinea Bissau, Sierra Leone, Liberia  and Ivory Coast.</em></strong> By Last Places</p>
                    <p><strong>Liberia</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Liberia offer?</strong><br>
                      Liberia is unique because of its  particular history linked like no other African country to the United States of  America. Slaves released from Virginia founded Liberia in 1822. This  relationship with America has marked the history of this small great African  country. Tom Sawyer style wood architecture, brutal beaches, primary jungles,  pygmy hippos, and live culture with an American flavor give Liberia a unique  flavor.<br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Monrovia is a curious capital,  somewhat unstructured but with its historic buildings, a couple of abandoned  hotels since the civil war, and vibrant markets. The National Museum of Liberia  is worth a visit for its collection of traditional carved and painted masks.<br>
                      -Careysburg is the closest thing to  a historic city in Liberia for its beautiful American South-style houses.  Founded in 1856 and named after the first Baptist missionary, the municipality  is 15 kilometers from Monrovia and an active agricultural community.<br>
                      - Robertsport, the first capital of  Liberia and a place of great beauty to rest and get to know the local culture  (Vai tribe) with its own writing (only a few old people between 70 and 80 years  old know how to write Vai).<br>
                      -The port city of Buchanan, is the  second largest urban agglomeration of Liberia but is isolated on the border  with Cote d'Ivoire. Interesting architecture<br>
                      -The Sierra de Nimba is shared with  neighboring Guinea Conakry and Cote d'Ivoire (UNESCO). Mount Wuteve is the  highest point in Liberia (4,500 meters).<br>
                      - Sapo National Park. The only  place in Africa, together with Taï National Park in Ivory Coast where there are  real possibilities to observe the rare and scarce pygmy hippopotamus.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Liberia:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Liberia</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Liberia.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccines in Liberia</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Liberia</strong><br>
                      Liberia is currently a safe country.  Avoid walking at night in some neighborhoods of Monrovia and avoid driving at  night to avoid accidents on bad roads. The police controls are not complicated  nor do they usually ask for money like in other countries.<br>
  <strong>Money in Liberia</strong><br>
                      Liberian dollars are the official  currency, but US dollars are the usual means of payment for visitors and are  accepted everywhere. Visitors must bring enough cash to cover their stay, since  ATMs and credit cards are almost nonexistent.<br>
  <strong>Schedule in Liberia</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging batteries cameras / mobiles  in Liberia</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 230 V. Frequency: 50 Hz.  Plugs: Type: C J<br>
  <strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><br>
  <strong>Best time to travel to Liberia - Climate of Liberia</strong><br>
                      Liberia is located just north of  the equator and therefore has an equatorial climate, very hot throughout the  year that is divided into two seasons: wet and dry. The rainy season is from  May to October, with very strong rainfall everywhere, while the dry season the  rest of the year, during which the Harmattan winds from the Sahara loaded with  sand blow inland and make the weather uncomfortable for residents and visitors.  Average temperatures are around 24 ° C throughout the year, and rarely rise  above 41 ° C, although the high humidity in the rainy season makes it feel  warmer than it really is. Last Places West Africa organizes trips throughout  the year.<br>
  <strong>Eating in Liberia</strong><br>
                      Monrovia is the center for dining  out and entertainment in Liberia with a surprising number of worthwhile  restaurants. International menus tend to be expensive, but Liberian and  Lebanese cuisine is tasty and affordable. Local restaurants serve indigenous  cuisine, heavy reliance on rice and hot sauces. <br>
  <strong>Photography in Liberia</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.<br>
  <strong>Books about Liberia</strong><br>
  <strong><em>Last Tribes of Guinea Bissau, Sierra Leone, Liberia  and Ivory Coast.</em></strong> By Last Places</p>
                    <p><strong>Ivory Coast</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Ivory Coast offer?</strong><br>
                      Ivory Coast was for many years  France&rsquo;s 'spoiled child', former colonizer of the country. France still has  many interests in the second largest cocoa producer in the world, but after the  civil war (2002-2007) the country has changed a lot. It remains an interesting  destination but in Last Places West Africa we have taken a turn and have  explored new areas to avoid the regions most affected by the conflict and that  have lost part of the original charm. Ivory Coast or Côte d'Ivoire is a country  with personality, varied, with a lot of contrast but a good guide who controls  ethnographic issues is key to getting the best out of the destination.<br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Komian rituals of the Agni tribe<br>
                      -Colonial Quarter of Grand Bassam<br>
                      -Explore Abidjan in depth,  neighborhoods, markets, and museums.<br>
                      - Art and masquerades of Baulé,  Dan, Senufo tribes.<br>
                      -Adobe architecture of Northern  tribes; Lobi, Senufo, and Malinke.<br>
                      -Taï National Park, refuge of the  pygmy hippopotamus and the Guinean chimpanzee.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Ivory Coast:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Ivory Coast</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Ivory Coast. </p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Ivory Coast</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Ivory Coast</strong><br>
                      After the Civil War (2002-2007)  some areas have been somewhat insecure and must be consulted before traveling  (central-north). In big cities you have to take precautions in what  neighborhoods and what hours, but nothing out of the ordinary. As always, Last  Places West Africa recommends moving with a guide around the country.<br>
  <strong>Money in Ivory Coast</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the CFA  Franc, common currency in several countries (former French colonies) of West  and Central Africa. You can exchange Euros for the local currency at airports,  banks, or exchange houses. The Last Places West Africa guide can help you  exchange money. The places that allow paying by credit card are counted, so  money must be carried in cash.</p>
