  <strong><em>Last Tribes of Guinea Bissau, Sierra Leone, Liberia  and Ivory Coast.</em></strong> By Last Places</p>
                    <p><strong>Mali</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Mali offer?</strong><br>
                      Mali is probably the best  destination in West Africa. Landscape, ethnography, history, and a unique  vernacular architecture in the World. For a couple of decades it has been the  main destination next to Senegal (less impressive) for many European travelers.  Mali does not disappoint ... you travel in time and enjoy unforgettable  experiences. Unfortunately, in recent times Mali does not live in peace ... and  that makes many people afraid to visit. Last Places West Africa continues to  organize trips to the Bandiagara Clift, Djené, and other iconic places of our  beloved Mali but things are not as they were and some areas such as Timbuktu  and the desert are no-go-zones. <br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Dogon country with its mythical  Bandiagara Clift<br>
                      -The last desert elephants in  Douentza<br>
                      - Tattooed Mbororo Nomads <br>
                      - Medieval city of Djené<br>
                      - Tuareg culture in Timbuktu<br>
                      - Debo Lake and adobe villages<br>
                      - Niger River and Bozo culture<br>
                      - Bambara masquerades in Segú region</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to Travel to Mali:</strong><br>
                      <strong>Tourist visa to travel to Mali</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Mali. Last Places West Africa helps to manage the visa.</p>
                    <p><strong>Mandatory vaccines in Mali</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Mali</strong><br>
                      Most of the tourist spots of Mali  can be visited without problem, except for the Saharan zone (including Timbuktu).  Clarified this, in the last months of 2019 there has been conflict between the  tribes Fulani and Dogon. This does not help to control the conflict in the  country that dates back to 2012, year in which the Tuareg rebelled against the  government with the support of Islamist groups coming from Algeria. This led  the French forces to intervene to make them retreat the following year. Since  then, Islamists have regained positions in the north and center, taking  advantage of ethnic rivalries.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Mali</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the CFA  Franc, common currency in several countries (former French colonies) of West  and Central Africa. You can exchange Euros for the local currency at airports,  banks, or exchange houses. The Last Places West Africa guide can help you  exchange money. The places that allow paying by credit card are counted, so  money must be carried in cash.</p>
                    <p><strong>Time in Mali</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging batteries cameras / mobiles  in Mali</strong><br>
                      Voltage: 220 V Plugs: Type C  Frequency: 50 Hz<br>
                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.<br>
  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>
  <strong>Best time to travel to Mali - Mali Climate</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips throughout the year. The climate of Mali knows three seasons that are  distributed unevenly throughout the year. (The rainy season lengthens as it  descends to the south).<br>
                      - The rainy season, runs from June  to September or October, reaching its peak in mid-August with an average  temperature of 25º.<br>
                      - The dry season, runs from March  to June in which the maximum temperatures are reached with 35º in Bamako and 32  in Timbuktu.<br>
                      - The cold and dry season goes from  October-November to February, with an average temperature of 25º, reaching the  minimum temperatures in the month of December.<br>
                      The Harmattan desert wind from the  Northeast, is unleashed immediately after the rainy season, contributing to  increase the dryness of the environment especially in the early afternoon. The  best period of the year for tourism, is from July to September in the rainy season  or from November to greater in the cold season.<br>
  <strong>Eating in Mali</strong><br>
  &nbsp;Some of the hotels have an  international-style restaurant and bar and serve international culinary art,  and most villages have small restaurants that serve local African dishes. The  hotel restaurants are open to non-residents. A particular specialty is La  Capitaine Sangha, a type of Nile perch served with hot chili, whole fried  plantains and rice. There is a limited choice of restaurants.<br>
                      Alcohol is available in bars (with  very late opening hours). Most people tend to drink fruit juice instead of  alcohol. Mali tamarind and guava juices are delicious.</p>
                    <p><strong>Photography in Mali</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.<br>
