                    <p><strong>Burkina Faso</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Burkina Faso offer?</strong><br>
                      Burkina Faso is &lsquo;transition&rsquo; a  country of between Mali, Ghana, Ivory Coast, and Niger ... we can say that it  has a bit of the 4 neighboring countries. That said, Burkina Faso also has its  own personality, with its Mossi nation occupying the epicenter and hundreds of  small tribes with their decaying adobe architecture (as in all of Africa), and  their scarifications (also disappearing)... Burkina Faso is an interesting country  that needs good guidance. A guide that knows how to get into places off the  beaten track (safe areas, of course) and who knows when ceremonies in villages  happen throughout the year. <br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      - Vernacular architecture of adobe  and stone from the Bobo, Mossi, Lobi, Dagara, Dogón, Kassena tribes.<br>
                      -Bella (former black slaves of the  Tuareg), Mbororo, and Tuareg nomadic tribes.<br>
                      -Scarifications and tattoos of the  Bobo-Bwa tribe of Mamboué village.<br>
                      - Gorom Gorom market (Thursdays)<br>
                      -Initiation rites (Ekonga) from Gurma  tribe of Yomba region (Niger border)<br>
                      - Oursi Lake, migratory birds sanctuary  in the Sahel.<br>
                      - Singou Faunal Reserve, connected to  the Arly and Pendjari National Park. the last 'healthy' ecosystem in this part  of West Africa with important herds of elephants and the last Sahelian lions.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Burkina Faso:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Burkina Faso</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Burkina Faso. It can be obtained on arrival or at the Embassy of Burkina  Faso in Paris. Last Places West Africa helps to manage the visa.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Burkina Faso</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Burkina Faso</strong><br>
                      Currently it is not recommended to  go to the north of Burkina Faso and specifically the strip between the towns of  Ouahigouya, Djibo, Dori, border areas with Niger and Mali. The rest of the  country is safe.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Burkina Faso</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the CFA  Franc, common currency in several countries (former French colonies) of West  and Central Africa. You can exchange Euros for the local currency at airports,  banks, or exchange houses. The Last Places West Africa guide can help you  exchange money. The places that allow paying by credit card are counted, so  money must be carried in cash.</p>
