                    <p><strong>Ghana</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Ghana offer?</strong><br>
                      Ghana is popular among travelers  nowadays. English-speaking nation, safe, and with good vibes. In Last Places  West Africa we like to highlight the colonial coastal heritage (slave trade)  and the Posuban Temples, unique in the Gulf of Guinea. It is a kind of altars (appeared  in the 1930s) that pay tribute to social or labor groups. In this coastal area  there is also something unique about Ghana that we like to highlight; themed  coffins. If the deceased was a fisherman, the wooden painted coffin will have  fish shape, if a pilot, the form of a plane, and so on ... Then there is the  Islamized and Animistic North, with Lobi and Kassena tribes with stunning adobe  architecture. A final surprise would be Mole National Park with herds of  elephants and spectacular scenery. Ghana is a good destination to introduce the  traveler in Africa for the first time. <br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Slave and military forts on the  coast of Ghana. Here is a list of the most interesting ones:<br>
                      -Goedehoop Fort or Fort of Good  Hope, in Senya Beraku<br>
                      -Cast Coast chateau<br>
                      -Fort Leysaemheyt or Fuerte  Paciencia, in Apam<br>
                      -Fort Amsterdam, in Kormantse<br>
                      -Fort of Santiago (Conraadsburg)  and Fort of San Jorge or Fort Elmina, in Elmina<br>
                      -Fort Batenstein, in Butri<br>
                      -Fort of San Sebastián, in Shama<br>
                      -Fort metallic cross, in Dixcove<br>
                      -Fort Vrendenburg, in Axim<br>
                      - Kakum National Park, last  remaining primary forest in this part of Africa.<br>
                      -Posuban Shrines (area between  Accra and Elmina)<br>
                      - Mole National Park<br>
                      - Sudanese style Larabanga Mosque <br>
                      - Ashanti vernacular architecture  in the villages of Abirim, Asawase, Asenemaso, Bodwease, Ejisu Besease, Adarko  Jachie, Edwenase, Kentinkrono, Patakro and Saaman). They are generally found in  northwest Kumasi, capital of the ancient Ashanti Kingdom, and also in Patakro,  south of Kumasi.<br>
                      - Ashanti funerals in Kumasi.<br>
                      - Initiation Female Rites (Dipo) of  the Krobo tribe in Lake Volta region.<br>
                      - Axim beaches near the Ivory Coast  border.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Ghana:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Ghana</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Ghana. Last Places Wst Africa helps manage it.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccines Ghana</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Ghana</strong><br>
                      Ghana is a safe country in general.  It is necessary to monitor certain areas of the border with Ivory Coast and to  avoid driving at night due to the crossing of people and animals.<br>
  <strong>Money in Ghana</strong><br>
                      The Cedi, pronounced 'sidi', which  in turn is divided into Pesewas. Better to bring cash because ATMs are rare  outside of Accra.</p>
                    <p><strong>Time in Ghana</strong></p>
                    <p>GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging batteries cameras / mobiles  in Ghana</strong><br>
                      The electric current is 230 volts  at 50 Hz (Plugs D / G)</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Ghana - Climate of Ghana</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips to Ghana throughout the year. The most abundant rains occur from May to  June and from September to October. In certain areas of the country, such as  the Ashanti Region, Central Region, Volta Region, the rains can be very  persistent and sometimes make traveling uncomfortable at these times (without  becoming unbearable).<br>
                      From December until February or  March, the &quot;Harmattan&quot;, wind from the desert makes its presence,  filling the atmosphere with dust; It is then very hot during the day, lowering  the night temperatures enough, it is the driest time. The hottest season is  next until the rains arrive, especially the months of March and April.</p>
                    <p><strong>Eating in Ghana</strong><br>
                      Traditional Ghanaian dishes often  consist of peanut stews, spicy meat and a little jollof, fufu or millet rice.  If you like street food, there are plenty of fried plantains, bean fritters and  yam fried or cooked. The restaurants offer an excellent combination of  international cuisine to satisfy all cravings. Traditional restaurants offer  authentic local food at very reasonable prices. Western-style cuisine can only  be found in large cities such as Accra and Kumasi, where there are shopping  centers. </p>
                    <p><strong>Photography in Ghana</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.</p>
                    <p><strong>Togo</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Togo offer?</strong><br>
                      Germany conquered Togo and designed  the country, imposing values ​​that can still be felt. Togo is an interesting  small West African country with surprising points such as forested mountains  bordering Ghana or the Tamberma Valley in the North. Not too much tourism and  deep culture make it an enjoyable destination.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -The coast of Togo (short) is worth  being traveled. In the center of the coastal strip is Togoville, with numerous  voodoo sanctuaries and the Catholic Cathedral. At the easternmost end of the  coast is Aného, ​​the spiritual center of the Guin-Mina people. Built on a  lagoon, this city was the first German administrative center on the coast and  later the capital of the region. Much of the colonial architecture still exists  and it is worth a visit.<br>
                      -Agbodrafo: Now it is a small and  quiet place half an hour from Lomé, this small town that was once Porto Seguro,  a Portuguese fort and an important station along the Costa de los Esclavos.  Although much evidence of Agbodrafo's cruel past has been erased, one can still  visit the Woold Home (also called the House of Slaves) and see the chains that  bound the slaves that were kept there.<br>
                      -Kpalimé, city surrounded by  several hills covered with tropical jungle, with small villages of the Ewé  ethnic group, deep valleys and spectacular waterfalls. Local guides can  organize tours of different lengths through the forest, to the summits of Mount  Agou Kloto, Kpoeta and the Tomegbe waterfalls. Once the center of coffee trade  and cocoa, the city still has some impressive colonial buildings, like the  German cathedral and the governor's house.<br>
                      -Small kingdoms throughout the  country.<br>
                      -Cases (Tata) of the Tamberma tribe  in the Northeast, Koutammakou region. Natural and anthropic landscape protected  by UNESCO.<br>
                      - Caves of Nano and Maproug: These  caves, inhabited by the Moba ethnic group during the periods of conflict in the  S-XVII, are located in the extreme north of Togo. The caves are part of a long  mountain range that stretches across the savannah towards Burkina Faso.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Togo:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Togo</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Togo. You get it at the Togolese Embassy in Paris or at the border if you  come from Benin or Ghana. Last Places West Africa helps manage the Togolese  visa.</p>
                    <p><strong>Togo mandatory vaccines</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Togo</strong><br>
                      In general terms, Togo is a safe  country but in the last decade there have been socio-political conflicts that  have tensed the environment a bit. All demonstrations and large gatherings  throughout the country should be avoided, as they could quickly turn into  violence. The area facing the sea in Lomé, especially around the Sarakawa hotel  is dangerous. Theft and theft are common, especially along the beach and in the  Lomé market areas. Attacks on pedestrians occur in broad daylight and night. </p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Togo</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the CFA  Franc, common currency in several countries (former French colonies) of West  and Central Africa. You can exchange Euros for the local currency at airports,  banks, or exchange houses. The Last Places West Africa guide can help you  exchange money. The places that allow paying by credit card are counted, so  money must be carried in cash.</p>
