                    <p><strong>Eating in Benin</strong><br>
                      Some popular dishes in the country  are beans with rice and Fufu (kind of bread, usually prepared from yams). The  usual soups that are served before the main course are Calalu (cooked with any  type of meat, oil, cassava, mustard, spinach, kale, kale, peeled and chopped tomatoes),  palm butter (made from palm nuts, garlic, onion, tomatoes and smoked fish),  peanut soup (prepared with chicken, peanuts, carrots, tomatoes, salt, garlic,  black pepper and peanut butter), pepper soup (cooked with goat meat, dried  shrimp, onion , salt, mint, utavi leaves) and Efo-riro (made of boiled fish,  palm oil, pepper, and onion).<br>
                      Lamb, chicken, fish, veal and pork  are common types of meat. Some of the most popular meat dishes in the country  are the fish stew of Dahomey (cooked with fish, fish broth or water, salt,  black pepper, flour, vegetable oil, red peppers or cayenne, onions and chopped  tomatoes), stewed lamb in peanut sauce (chicken breast, oil, salt, pepper,  onion), Gari Pinon (beef, oil, onion, tomato, pepper)), Ago Glain (crabs, oil, black  pepper, vinegar, leaves laurel, tomatoes, lemon, parsley, cloves, onions and  Pili Pili), Benineses enjoy sweet dishes such as Kanyah (sugar, rice and  peanuts), Kashata Peokut, grated peanut, banana leaves and palm oil) and lemon  custard (prepared with butter, sugar, cornstarch, eggs, milk and grated lemon).</p>
