                    <p><strong>Nigeria</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Nigeria offer?</strong><br>
                      We like to define Nigeria as  African Pakistan; overpopulated, Islamized (in part) and reputed to be  dangerous but when you know it, you fall in love. For Last Places West Africa,  Nigeria is a treasure. A varied, rich country, full of surprises and that does  not leave anyone indifferent. We know that it will never be a commercial or  mass destination, partly we like it for that ... destination for experienced  and curious palates.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      - Yoruba old cities, full of  decadent and fantastic architecture.<br>
                      - Cross River primary forests,  refuge of the Cross River gorilla.<br>
                      -Yoruba religion and shrines (Southwest).<br>
                      -Tattooed tribes from Niger State.<br>
                      - Fulani Gerewol from Nigeria.<br>
                      -Hausa northern Emirates.<br>
                      -Durbar Festival (North)<br>
                      -Alantika Mountains and mountain  tribes.<br>
                      -Biafra and Igbo culture  (Southeast).<br>
                      -Masquerades from South-Central  Nigeria.<br>
                      -Okrikra Island and fattening  ceremony.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to Travel to Nigeria:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Nigeria</strong><br>
                      The tourist visa is mandatory to  enter Nigeria. Last Places West Africa helps manage it.</p>
                    <p><strong>Mandatory vaccines in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      As a company specializing in  tourism we have never had major problems in Nigeria. The northeastern region  (Maidiguri) has traditionally been the operating center of Boko Haram but is  currently very small and basically operates in Lake Chad ... are areas that we  do not usually visit. Another area where it is advised to take precaution in  Rivers State (Southeast oil) by armed groups in the area of ​​the mangroves but  this does not affect the scarce tourism but workers of oil companies. In large  cities such as Lagos or Ibadan you have to be careful according to what hours  and in what neighborhoods. The key is to go with a professional guide who knows  how to move around these mega-cities.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      The official currency of Nigeria is  the Naira. They easily change Euros and American Dollars in banks, hotels and  on the street. The Last Places West Africa guide helps manage the change if  necessary.<br>
                      In Nigeria, it is common to pay in  cash, so it is necessary to bring enough money that we plan to spend. Credit  cards are rarely accepted outside of Lagos.</p>
                    <p><strong>Schedule in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      GMT / UTC + 1. </p>
                    <p><strong>Electricity and charging batteries cameras / mobiles  in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      In Nigeria the common voltage is  230 V. The frequency is 50 Hz. The plugs and sockets are of type D / G.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Nigeria - Climate of Nigeria</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips throughout the year, although the best months are between October and  December. Nigeria has two distinct climate zones. Along the coast, the  equatorial sea air mass allows high humidity and heavy rainfall between April  and October.<br>
                      To the north, the tropical  continental air mass carries dry and dust-laden winds ('harmatán' wind) from  the Sahara. The temperature varies considerably with the season, as does the  rainfall, which is much higher in the south. Between March and May,  temperatures can reach 45º C north of the country. On the coast, the average  temperature is between 25º C and 30º C.<br>
  <strong>Eating in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      Nigeria's cuisine is a rich blend  of traditionally African carbohydrates such as yams and cassava, as well as  vegetable soups made from native green leaves. A soup based on the palm fruit  called banga is typical of the country.<br>
                      Praised by the Nigerians for the  strength it gives, the Garri is a cassava grain powder that can be easily  consumed as a meal and is quite cheap. The yam is, whether fried in oil or  crushed to make a mashed potato, is different from green peas and is very  popular. The meat is also quite ingested and Nigeria Suya, a barbecue, as a  method of roasting meat, is a well-known dish. The fermented palm products are  used to make a traditional liquor, palm wine, since it is fermented from  cassava.</p>
                    <p><strong>Photography in Nigeria</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.</p>
