                    <p><strong>Gabon</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does Gabon offer?</strong><br>
                      Gabon is a good destination for  nature lovers, also for those travelers wanting to disconnect from the World  and Humanity ... Gabon has an extension half of France and only one and a half  million inhabitants. Thanks to low human density and an oil-based economy,  Gabon is a country covered with primary and secondary forests, forested hills,  swamps, tropical rivers, and tropical savannahs. It is a natural paradise. In  the 1990s, the idea was to turn Gabon into African Costa Rica ... it has not  been achieved yet, but the potential is there. Safe, calm and with great  diversity of ecosystems that are a delight for the seekers of rare animals such  as the mandrills, the bongo, the western lowland gorilla, the dwarf crocodile  ... and a unique sighting in Africa, elephants walking along the beach in  Loango National Park. In fact, our name 'Last Places' was inspired by a report  by National Geographic that described Loango National Park as' The Last Place  on Earth. We have been operating in Gabon since 2008 and have become expert  fixers in this magnificent African destination.<br>
  <strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      -Mandrill herds in the Lopé National  Park (Best sighting time: European summer).<br>
                      -Jungle elephants roaming along the  beaches of Loango National Park (Best sighting time: European winter).<br>
                      -Loango Lodge and the unique  experience of observing the African jungle top fauna in an exclusive comfort;  western lowland gorillas, sitatungas, jungle elephants, bongos, wild hogs,  chimpanzees, red buffalos, 'marine' hippos, humpback whales, leopards ...<br>
                      -Lambarené, colonial city, surrounded  by beautiful tropical lakes with hippos, and the story behind Dr. Albert  Schweitzer.</p>
                    <p>- Ivindo National Park, last frontier.  Clearings in the jungle where you can observe western lowland gorillas, jungle  elephants, and bongos.</p>
                    <p>-Lekedi private Reserve to ensure  the sighting of mandrills and be able to photograph them closely.</p>
                    <p>- Powerful Bwiti rituals in Central  Gabon.</p>
                    <p>- Spend some days with the Babongo  pygmies in their food gathering camps in the middle of the Gabonese jungle.</p>
                    <p>-Explore one of Gabon&rsquo;s remote  protected areas; Minkebé, Plateaux Bateké, Monts de Cristal, Mayumba, among  others ... after the physical and mental effort, give yourself a few days of  total relaxation on the beaches of Pointe Denis ... or take a leap to the  paradise of Sao Tome or Principe, just opposite the Gabonese coast.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to Gabon:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Gabon</strong><br>
                      The entry visa to Gabon is  mandatory. Last Places West Africa helps manage it.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Gabon</strong><br>
                      Yellow fever. Recommended  prophylaxis against malaria.</p>
                    <p><strong>Security in Gabon</strong><br>
                      Gabon is not a particularly  insecure country, but it is beginning to present some danger, especially in the  capital. In fact, petty thefts are common in urban areas, but violent crimes  are not common, although they can occur. The visitor should also be careful  with pickpockets, although it is not a particularly conflictive country.</p>
                    <p><strong>Money in Gabon</strong><br>
                      The national currency is the CFA  Franc, common currency in several countries (former French colonies) of West  and Central Africa. You can exchange Euros for the local currency at airports,  banks, or exchange houses. The Last Places West Africa guide can help you  exchange money. The places that allow paying by credit card are counted, so  money must be carried in cash.</p>
