                      To charge the batteries during the  camping days, we will have the plugs of the vehicles themselves as well as a  generator that will facilitate.</p>
                    <p><strong>Best time to travel to Gabon - Climate of Gabon</strong><br>
                      Last Places West Africa organizes  trips throughout the year. The key is to know the best time to see the fauna that  interests the traveler: mandrills in Lopé, elephants on the beaches of Loango,  or turtle nesting in Mayumba for example. Gabon has an equatorial climate, hot  and humid all year round. The small rainy season lasts from October to December  and the great rainy season from February to April. Dry seasons from May to  September (large) and from December to January (small). Although it seems  incredible, the rainy season is the most propitious for tourism, since the days  are sunnier, falling precipitations during the night, being also these of short  duration. During the dry season we found the cloudy sky.<br>
                      We have been in the great rainy  season (April), and it has hardly rained, which has allowed us to make many  walks through the jungle without any problem.</p>
                    <p><strong>Eating in Gabon</strong><br>
                      The cuisine of Gabon is influenced  by French cuisine, so its dishes are somewhat more elaborate than those of  other countries in the area. The diet is mainly based on fish and shellfish,  stewed or grilled, accompanied by vegetables such as okra or cassava leaves. In  almost all meals, rice or manioc is served to complete the menu, which ends  with fruit as the usual dessert. The meat is less consumed, but we can find  chicken, pork, antelope or monkey. As drinks, it is worth mentioning the tea  and a wine made with sugar cane. Gabon smells of cassava leaves, eggplant, palm  oil, grilled chicken, roasted fish, peanuts, chilli, banana, mango and  pineapple.<br>
  <strong>Photography in Gabon</strong><br>
                      Avoid photographing military or  police controls. Better not to photograph official buildings and ask permission  to take pictures of people or their houses.<br>
