                    <p><strong>Sao Tome and Principe</strong><br>
                      <strong>What does São Tomé and Príncipe offer?</strong><br>
                      Paradise islands, with great virgin  beaches, nice people, and lush forested hills. The place to disconnect and get  lost of the World. Ideal extension after an intense trip through Nigeria, an  ethnographic route through southern Angola, or a jungle safari through Gabon,  the 3 countries connected to the Sao Tome and Principe archipelago.</p>
                    <p><strong>Last Places West Africa recommends:</strong><br>
                      Portuguese colonial decadent architecture.<br>
                      -Panoramic of the Cão Grande peak,  a volcanic spire of just over 600 meters that nourishes the landscape of the  Obo Natural Park on the island of Santo Tomé.<br>
                      -The spawning of sea turtles on the  pristine beaches of Praia Grande (Prince) or Praia Jalé i Inhame (São Tomé).  And go out to watch whales by boat (both can be done in São Tomé and in  Príncipe).<br>
                      -Trekking in the Obo, either in São  Tomé or in Príncipe (in the latter it is almost unexplored).<br>
                      -To know inside one of the roças  (plantations) of the colonial period that continue to function today as Roça  Paciencia (Prince) or Monte Café (Santo Tomé).<br>
                      - Take a dip in Praia Banana, Praia  Macaco or Praia Boi, the most holy trinity of the paradisiacal beaches of  Príncipe.</p>
                    <p><strong>Information to travel to São Tomé and Príncipe:</strong></p>
                    <p><strong>Tourist visa to travel to Sao Tome and Principe</strong><br>
                      You do not need a visa to visit Sao  Tome and Principe if the trip does not exceed 15 days and you are a citizen of  the European Union, the United States or any Portuguese-speaking country. You  only need to bring your passport with a validity of at least 3 months. In the  case of wanting to spend more time in the island country, it is essential to  have a visa, which must be requested from the São Tomé and Príncipe Embassy in  Lisbon.</p>
                    <p><strong>Compulsory vaccinations in Sao Tome and Principe</strong><br>
                      Only the yellow fever vaccine  primer is required if it comes from a country where this disease is endemic or  present. Malaria is practically eradicated in the islands, although there are  still some isolated cases every year (in São Tomé more than in Príncipe) so  there are health centers where they recommend taking malaria prophylaxis and  others that do not give much importance. Other recommended vaccines are typhoid  fever, hepatitis B or tetanus, although for almost any country in the world and  for people who travel a lot throughout the year.</p>
